{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/00279558893/1946041901/0701.xml":{"full_text":"more about\nGARDENS\nfrom page one\nsnot of the South, and along\ncity\u2019s streets.\nBut the>' didn stoP with\n,zaieas. They also planted 991\n'rdenias, camellias, roses, wis\n\u201c\u2018\u25a0a, small flowering trees, and\nshrubs.\nThis, the Babylonians figure, is\nenough flowers to keep the em\n\u201eress and all her court in cor\nses for several decades and\nn some, a fact which really\nflusters the Babylonian florists.\n293 Shade Trees\nThe Babylonian tree-transplant\nrs are heckled too. They find\n\u2022hemselves under the huge shadow\ncaSt by the 293 share trees Snell\u2019s\n\u201e?n have set out since January 1.\nAH these adult flowers and trees\nalready in operation, so to speak,\nare worry enough to the Baby\nlonians. What, really has them\njiarmed is Wilmington\u2019s younger\nfloral generation.\nSnell\u2019s men, you see, have also\ntansplanted 6,168 azaleas and 114\ncamellia japonicas from the lining\nout beds to the nursery rows in\n*^e Greenfield park nursery. These\ns urdy youngsters constitute a\nreal future threat to the Baby\nlonians\u2019 supremacy.\nAll ip all, Snell and his men\nave handled, with dextrous\nbotanical hands, 16,237 trees, vines,\nshrubs, and other members of the\nplant kingdom since the first of\nthe year.\nIt s a staggering total. Better\nwatch out, Babylonia.\nMORE ABOUT\nCALF\nFROM PAGE ONE\nhimself, said, yes, he could\nsee that, and he walked down\nand took hold of the rope.\nSomebody prodded the calf. He\ngrudgingly got up, turned around,\nand aimed a nervous kick at the\npresident.\nThere was a second\u2019s embar\nrassed silence. Secret service\nmen, unskilled in the unique art\nof protecting presidents from\ncalves, looked frustrated. Mr. Tru\nman looked mildly surprised, and\nmildly amused.\nAgain Fuller tried to save the\nsituation.\nHe began to talk about the calf\u2019s\nantecedents, particularly his\ngrandma. Seems the old lady was\na champion, and mooed them down\nin the better cowv social circles.\nHere it came out why a calf\nshould be visiting Mr. Truman.\nHe had caught a plane and had\ncome all this way to invite the\nPresident to attend the Birming\nham, Ala., rodeo.\nFuller said Mr. Truman could\nhave the calf.\nIn spite of the nice pasture (the\nonly time the calf looked even re\nmotely happy was after sampling\nsome White House clover) Mr.\nTruman said he would give the\nanimal to the Emergency Famine\ncommittee.\nThe President tossed the calf\na final, cheerful beam. The calf\nglowered back.\nThe interview was over.\nVENETIAN BLINDS\nVIA SIZE BLINDS MADE AND\nREFINISHED\nSTRICKLAND VENETIAN\nBLIND WORKS\nPhone 8404. Castle Hayne Road\nt#R l^GER,\u00a3 I\nAMERICA\u2019S WASH WORD 16\\\n-Z77774*\nThe Heat Number 1\n(8 Sevens A Four)\nS^FUELCO. J\ni\nFARRAR\nTR ANSFER STORAGE\nWAREHOUSE\nDIAL 5317\nCORNDALE\n100 PROOF\nCORN WHISKY\n4/5 QUART PINTS\n*3.05 *1.90\nDISTILLED AND BOTTLED BY\nPENNDALI DISTILLING C0<\nSHAEFFERSTOWN, PA.\n[im oil\nStandard Oil \u201cESSOHEAT\u201d\nOil Burner Service\nL iLu\u00a3SEi 15P\nr~\nNOTICE\nBEER WINE DEALERS\nCITY AND COUNTY LICENSE EXPIRE APRIL 30ih, 1946\nBefore new license can be issued it is necessary to\nfile an application to sell beer or wine with the under\nsigned.\nAny person, firm or corporation selling without\na license is liable to indictment for violating said or\ndinance.\nC. R. MORSE,\nCity County Tax Collector\nspecial\nEASTER VALUE!\nFRUIT CAKES\n2.00 and 3.00 Values\n.00\n1.00 Values\n50c\nMake this an Easter of hospitality. For your\nfamily dinner or \u201ccompany spread,\u201d you\u2019ll\nfind that fruit cake will make a perfect des\nsert.\nMAIN FLOOR\nidelkMUams* fo\nmore about\nelection\nFROM PAGE ONE\nJ\u00ae t'?at \u00b0mtce Was confirmed\nby the elections board. First\nvictory for the mere males of\nNew Hanover High was\nachieved by Malcolm Crawford\nwho was named president of\nthe Junior class for the next\nschool year, while Larry De\ngenhart, evened the score for\nthe boys in the matter of top\nhonors when he won the presi\ndency of the Sophomore class.\nCatherine Crowe was elected\nvice president of the Junior\nclass, while Ann Post won the\nsecretary-treasurership.\nThe result of the elections left\nrun-over contests necessary for the\nVice presidency and secretary\ntreasurer offices in the Senior class\nand also for the same offices in the\nSophomore class. For the Senior\nclass vice presidency, Jeannine\nStanley and Flora Mclver will en\nter the run-off race, while Ed Pitts\nand Virginia Hatch will again con\ntest for the secretary-treasury\nlost.\nOfficial tabulations of the vot\ning which closed at 3:30 yesterday\nafternoon left Joan Warshauer and\nAudrey Strong in a run-off race\nfor the vice presidency of the\nSophomore class while a three-cor\n1 ered contest developed for the un\ndecided' office of secretary\ntreasurer between Jean Pullen,\nJanice Harvell, and Betty Hill.\nFinal deciding elections will be\nheld with the next 10 days, ac\ncording to Catherine Harriss, chair\nman of the Student board of elec\ntions, which according to school\nofficials, has done a bang-up job\nin supervising the elections for\nthe various offices.\nmunjCi adulii\nFOOD\nFROM PAGE ONE\nwheat to deliver their grain now\nunder a plan aimed to proted\nthem if prices increase later.\n4. The government is expected\nsoon to request farmers to cu|\nthis year\u2019s pig crop by at leasi\nfive per cent below last year\u2019s\nlevel, to conserve scarce feed\ngrains.\n5. Secretary Anderson praised\nArgentina\u2019s \u201cwonderful coopera\ntion\u201d in increasing wheat exports\nabroad.\n6. Still hanging fire are Ameri\ncan-British-Canadian negotiations\non a proposal by Anderson that\nthe British divert to famine areas\na large portion of the wheat im\nports they are scheduled to re\nceive before July 1.\n7. The Far Eastern commission\nordered an investigation of U. S.\nfood shipments to Japan after Sir\nCarl Berendsen of New Zealand\nexpressed concern over the pos\nsibility that preference might be\nshown to Japan or other Axis\npowers. Secretary Anderson had\nsaid earlier that more than 500,\n000 tons of food will be sent to\nJapan in the first half of this\nyear. President Truman told the\nASNE members that some of the\nworst starvation areas were in\nJapan and Germany.\nMORE ABOUT\nPORTER\nFROM PAGE ONE\ntrol,\u201d gave attention too to other\namendments in the House measure,\nnotably the Wolcott-Crawford pro\nvision requiring a \"reasonable\u201d\nprofit on each product, the pro\nhibitions against OPA\u2019s require\nment that manufacturers turn out\na certain proportion of low priced\nclothing and that retailers in some\neases absorb part of the price in\ncreases given manufacturers, and\nthe order to liquidate subsidies.\nThe price administrator patiently\nwas pointing his remarks at the\nSenate, which gets next crack at\nthe price- control law.\nSo also was Chester Bowles,\nstabilization director, when he con\nferred for 35 minutes Thursday\nmorning with President Truman\nand then told newsmen he did not\nsee how price controls could be\nmaintained under the measure\nwhich the House finally passed 355\nto 42.\nMeanwhile Lew Hahn, general\nmanager of the National Retail Dry\nGoods association, issued a state\nment giving his \u201cpersonal convic\ntion that the House in some re\nspects has gone too far.\u201d\n\"The way in which the House\nit Representatives has seized the\noit and run away with the bill to\nsxtend the Emergency Price Con\ntrol act can be ascribed only to the\nfanaticism displayed by Chester\nBowles and the OPA organization\nin the arbitrary stubbornness of\ntheir administration,\u201d Hahn said.\nLOOKING FOR WIN\nDAVIDSON, April 18.\u2014(jT*)\u2014Still\nseeking a victory after four starts,\nDavidson\u2019s baseball team will hav*\ntwo chances against Virginia clubs\nDver the week-end. The Wildcats\nwill be at Roanoke College Friday\nand at Washington and Lee Satur\nday.\n1\nRENEWAL OF BONDS\nAPPROVED BY WHA\nON 190 EMPLOYES\nRenewal of fidelity bonds\non 190 employes was authoriz\ned by the Wilmington Hous\ning Authority a a meeting\nApril 16, it was disclosed yes\nterday by B. H. Marshall, Jr.,\ncomptroller of the Authority.\nThe renewal of the bonds,\nproviding for $10,000 on each\nemploye, was made with the\nLumberman\u2019s Mutual Casual\nty company, through the com\npany\u2019s local agents, H. G.\nLatimer and Son.\nTotal anticipated amount of\nthe premium, which also in\ncludes bonding of officers\nauthorized to sign and count\nersign checks in the amount\nof *50,000, was $697.19, which\nMarshall said compared with\nlast year\u2019s premium of *1,\n29,4.02.\nMORE ABOUT\nSPAIN\nFROM PAGE ONE\nPolish proposal charging Spain is\na potentially explosive threat to\nFrance and a long-range menace\nto the wrold in ihe atomic age.\nAmendment Offered\nLt.-Col. W. R. Hodgson, the\nAustralian delegate, offered an\namendment to the Polish resolu\ntion for a break with Spain, ask\ning that e five-man sub-committee\ninvestigate the Spanish situation\nand report back to the council by\nMay 17.\nCadogan discounted the charges\nlaid Wednesday by Polish Rele\ngate Oscar Lange and declared a\nbreak in relations would remove\nagencies of the Allied governments\nin Madrid which now keep tabs on\nGerman activities in Spain.\nNo Check\nThe British delegate said that ir\nthe event of a break \u201cthe field\nwould be left free to the Germans\nin Spain and we should have nc\ncheck upon them.\u201d\nThe high point of disagreemeni\nbetween Russia and Britain broughl\nforth their opposed contentions or\nthe question of whether the Span\nish situation should rightfully fall\ninto the category of- an interna:\nproblem or a matter for world at\ntention and action.\nMORE ABOUT\nBUILDING\nFROM PAGE ONE\n7\nwhich was to cost owners a com\nbined total of 38,300.\nMaterial Purchased\nMrs. Strickland said that these\nbuildings were under construction\nin some cases and that in all in\nstar-'-s material had been pur\nchased for construction.\nShe pointed out that many of the\nworkmen employed on the banned\nprojects are ex-servicemen. While\nthey are assured homes under the\nveteran priority regulations, they\nfear unemployment will follow en\nforcement of CPA\u2019s policy.\nWrightsville Beach\nAt Wrightsville Beach 35 con\nstruction workers stand to lose\nwage hours by the CPA\u2019s stoppage\norders.\nFive building projects, including\none structure valued at $14,000;\none $8,000; one $7,500, and two\nvalued at $6,000 are scheduled for\nabandonment. They are now un\nder construction.\nTwo other Wrightsville structures\nwere cancelled before construction\nwas under way.\nMUK\u00a3 ABUtX\nBLAST\nFROM PAGE ONE\nat the lowest level of the sloping\ntunnel which rtins under New\nHope river.\nOther workers some distance\nremoved from the explosion point\nescaped with minor burns or ill\neffects from the fumes.\nA rescue squad from Radford\ndonned gas masks and made its\nway to the site shortly after the\nexplosion.\nDie From Burns\nEleven were found dead of\nburns. The twelfth miner, Paul\nPrice, was brought to the surface\nbut died without regaining con\nsciousness at a hospital here.\nRescue workers from West Vir\nginia assisted the Virginia squad\nin bringing out the others, all of\nwhom could be recognized.\nAll of the dead were residents\nof McCoy, a small community\nwhose main source of livelihood\nis from the- mine. They were Paul\nPrice, Harman Siffcrd, Cecil Han\ncock, J. P. Price, Frank Price,\nC. R. Johnson, Ed Ritter, Frank\nDeweese, John Duncan, Dave Gra\nham and J. L. Sarver.\nOPA GRANTS\nWASHINGTON, April 18\u2014(A5)\u2014\nOPA Thursday raised retail price\nceilings on new refrigerators by\nfour percent over March, 1942\nlevels to offset higher production\ncosts.\nThe agency granted manufact\nurers an eight per cent increase,\nwhich it Said will be reflected in\nfull at retail.\nGOLF TOURNEY TODAY\nWILSON, April 18 More\nthan 100 golfers will compete in the\nsecond Eastern Carolina amateur\ntournament, a 36-hole affair, at\nthe Wilson Country club Friday.\nAvery Beck of Raleigh, will defend\nhis title against a strong field that\nincludes 1945 runner up Johnny\nParabow of Kinston.\nMORE ABOUT\nCLARK\nFROM PAGE ONE\ntain to okay the reduced amount.\nFollowing the Senate\u2019s approval,\nonly a presidential veto\u2014an ex\ntreme improbability\u2014can stop the\nbill. Barring this, the $1,000,000\nCape Fear allotment will allow the\ndredging of the Cape Fear river\nto go ahead on schedule in July\nas already planned by Col. George\nW. Gillette, U. S. district chief\nof engineer*.\nMORE ABOUT\nGASOLINE\nFROM PAGE ONE\nThe Standard Oil company, which\nholds the expiring contract, sub\nmitted a flat bid of 13.89 cents as\nagainst its present flat rate of\n14.92.\nThe state board of award is sche\nduled to meet today to place\ncontract.\nThe 20,000,000 gallons of gaso\nline for state use is a drop in the\nbucket to the total amount of gaso\nline and other fuel which is ex\npected to flow through the Wil\nmington port this year.\nIn 1945, with the war still going\nf\non, 588,949 tons of petroleum prod\nucts were handled here, a 400 per\ncent increase over the 1944 figure.\nIn the first three months of 1946\n48 tankers docked and discharged\ncargo here. These, plus 16 cargo\nvessels, made a total of 64 ships\ncoming through the local port from\nJanuary 1 to March 31.\nThe grand total of ships through\nthe port in 1945 was only 110.\nMORE ABOUT\nMARSHALL\nFROM PAGE ONE\nThe mere presence of Marshall,\nspecial U. S. Envoy to China,\nprompted some political observers\nto assert that some kind of ar\nagreement would be reached\nspeedily.\nIt was known that both the Com\nmunists and the government had\nanxiously awaited the General\u2019s\narrival in the hope of reaching a\nface-saving compromise.\nBACKACHE,\nLEG PAINS MAY\nBE DANGER SIGN\nOf Tired Kidneys\nIf backache and leg pains are making yon\nmiserable, don\u2019t just complain and do nothing\nabout them. Nature maybe warning you that\nyour kidneys need attention.\nThe kidneys a re N ature\u2019s chief way of taking\nexcess acids and poisonous waste out of the\nblood. They help most people pass about 3\npints a day.\nIf the 15 mile3 of kidney tubes and filters\ndon\u2019t work well, poisonous waste matter stays\nin the blood. These poisons may start nagging\nbackaches, rheumatic pains, leg pains, loss of\npep and energy, getting up nights, swelling,\npuffiness underthe eyes, headaches and dizzi\nness. Frequent or scanty passages with smart\ningandburning sometimes shows there is some\nthing wrong with your kidneys or bladder.\nDon't wait! Ask your druggist for Doan\u2019s\nPills, a stimulant diuretic, used successfully\nby millions for over 40 years. Doan\u2019s give\nhappy relief and will help the 15 miles of\nkidney tubes flush out poisonous waste from\nthe blood. Get Doan\u2019s Pills.\nMORE ABOUT\nTRAINMEN\nFROM PAGE ONE\nri'i\"\"\nin 15 non-operating an< three op\nerating unions.\nThe non-operating unions 'nave\nsince asked for an additional 14\ncents per hour increase.\nThe United States harvests about\n250 tons of honey annually.\nSEE OUR NEW\nSPBIM6 FELT BATS\nCibsea's Baberdasbtry\n_ North Front Street\n\u25a0KV\\\\\\VV\\V\\X\\X^NV\\V\\V\\NV\\VVVVVVVV\\VVV\\XXV\\V\ne There is no finer gift than this\nbeautiful netv 19-jetvel Lady Elgin.\nAn Elgin Do Luxe ixth smart aim*\nplicity of both cast: and ftninribr.\nWarti me graduates mav have\nhad to wait for the traditional\ngift of an Elgin. But now they\nand the class of '46 can hav e the\nmasterpiece of American watch*\nmaking a beautiful, tin,\ntimed Elgin.\nMad* In America by Aaierfcen Craftsmen\nAn example of the handtome neve\n*ar-timed Elgin Watches for men*\nSTANLEY S\nPhone 4095 109 Princess\nfKMHl\nROEBUCK AND CoJH|\n45 PLATE BATTERY ALLSTATE MOTOR TUNE SEAL BEAM KITS SI